{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}} {{Infobox person |name=Daniel Vávra |image= |image_size= |caption=Daniel Vávra in 2013 |birth_date={{birth date and age|df=yes|1975|9|2}}<ref name=justice>Obchodní rejstřík na justice.cz, IČ 24155489, Warhorse Studios s.r.o. (formerly Prague Game Studios s.r.o.), Czech</ref> |birth_place=[[Rychnov nad Kněžnou]], [[Czechoslovakia]] |occupation=[[Video game writer]], [[game director]], [[game designer]] }}
'''Daniel Vávra''' (born 2 September 1975) is a Czech [[video game writer]], [[game director|director]], [[game designer|designer]] and co-founder of [[Warhorse Studios]]. He is best known as the author of crime action video games ''[[Mafia (video game)|Mafia]]'' and ''[[Mafia II]]'' and the medieval role-playing game ''[[Kingdom Come: Deliverance]]''.
== Biography == Daniel Vávra was born in [[Rychnov nad Kněžnou]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.giantbomb.com/daniel-vavra/3040-25892/|title=Daniel Vávra (Person) - Giant Bomb|publisher=|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopstage.cz/rozhovory/jay-diesel-v-rozhovoru-pro-hiphopstage-nabizi-nejen-slibenej-new-mixtape-ke-stazeni|title=Jay Diesel v rozhovoru pro HipHopStage nabízí nejen slíbenej new mixtape ke stažení!|publisher=HipHopStage}}</ref> before moving to [[Prague]].<ref name=justice/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reflex.cz/clanek/komentare/48176/recka-pomsta-ceskym-vyvojarum-dan-vavra-polemizuje-s-janem-a-novakem.html|title=Řecká pomsta českým vývojářům. Dan Vávra polemizuje s Janem A. Novákem|work=Reflex.cz}}</ref> He has partial [[History of the Jews in the Czech Republic|Jewish]] ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|title=DanielVavra|url=https://twitter.com/DanielVavra/status/959954427103907840|publisher=Twitter|date=3 February 2018}}</ref> Since childhood, Vávra has enjoyed working with computers, drawing comics, and taking photos.<ref name=dan-bio>{{cite web|url=http://www.danielvavra.com/bio|title=Bio - Hellboy|publisher=danielvavra.com}}</ref> He studied at the School of Applied Arts in [[Turnov]] and started his career as a graphic designer at advertising company TIPA. He has written numerous articles for the Czech gaming magazine ''Level''<ref name=dan-bio/> and other gaming magazines, and is also a passionate player of [[paintball]].<ref name=dan-bio/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.danielvavra.com/articles/military-paintball-community-camping2010|title=Military Paintball Community Camping 2010 < Articles - Hellboy|publisher=danielvavra.com}}</ref> He was also an active [[demoscene]]r, under the pseudonym ''Hellboy'', as part of the group ''Broncs''.<ref>http://zine.bitfellas.org/article.php?zine=13&id=19</ref>
===Illusion Softworks/2K Czech=== In 1998, Vávra joined [[2K Czech|Illusion Softworks]] as a 2D artist. His first project was ''[[Hidden and Dangerous]]'', for which he created some textures.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mafia2.scorpions.cz/novinka/rozhovor-s-danielem-vavrou|title=Mafia 2 - Rozhovor s Danielem Vávrou - na Scorpions.cz|publisher=}}</ref> His next project was the highly acclaimed ''[[Mafia: The City of Lost Heaven]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/mafia|title=Mafia for PC Reviews|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> for which he was the lead designer, screenwriter and director. He later became the leading figure of Illusion Softworks's Prague subsidiary<ref>{{cite web|url=http://games.tiscali.cz/tema/na-cem-pracuje-prazska-pobocka-illusionu-21601|title=Na čem pracuje pražská pobočka Illusionu?|author=Tiscali|work=Games.cz}}</ref> and also worked on ''[[Wings of War (video game)|Wings of War]]'', released in 2004.<ref name=mobygames/> He worked on another project, ''Hi-Tech'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mfnk2xw4ssQ|title=HiTech|work=YouTube}}</ref> but it was cancelled.{{cn|date=March 2017}} His last project for Illusion Softworks (renamed as 2K Czech) was ''[[Mafia II]]''. He left the studio in 2009.{{cn|date=March 2017}}
===Warhorse Studios=== In 2011, Vávra co-founded [[Warhorse Studios]]. He is currently working on ''[[Kingdom Come: Deliverance]]'', a [[role-playing video game]] that uses [[Cry Engine 3]] set in a medieval-themed open world environment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-01-21-i-do-care-for-a-next-gen-medieval-rpg-with-no-fantasy|title=I do care for a next-gen medieval RPG with no fantasy • Eurogamer.net|date=22 January 2014|work=Eurogamer.net|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> The game was set to be delivered in Q4 2015 through episodic iterations, and was successfully funded via [[Kickstarter]].
On 9 November 2012, Vávra led a protest against the arrest of I. Buchta and M. Pezlar, Bohemia Interactive ''[[Arma 3]]'' developers arrested during their holiday on the Greek island [[Lemnos]]. The protest was held outside the Greek embassy in Prague.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-11-29-jailed-arma-3-devs-send-letter-from-prison-as-czech-protests-escalate|title=Jailed ArmA 3 devs send letter from prison as Czech protests escalate • Eurogamer.net|date=29 November 2012|work=Eurogamer.net|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref>
On 2 April 2015, Vávra ([[Warhorse Studios]]) announced that ''[[Kingdom Come: Deliverance]]'' was delayed until Summer 2016<ref>{{cite web|title=Kingdom Come: Deliverance delayed until summer 2016|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-04-02-kingdom-come-deliverance-delayed-until-2016|website=Eurogamer.net|accessdate=15 April 2018}}</ref>, and the game was later delayed until 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kingdom Come: Deliverance delayed until next year|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-05-23-kingdom-come-deliverance-delayed-until-next-year|website=Eurogamer.net|accessdate=15 April 2018}}</ref> The game was released on February 13, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kingdom Come: Deliverance release date, platforms and gameplay news|url=https://www.techadvisor.co.uk/new-product/game/kingdom-come-deliverance-news-3637546/|website=Tech Advisor|accessdate=15 April 2018}}</ref>
== Political views == He has been a vocal critic of censorship and what he believes is a [[Progressivism|progressive]] [[bias]] in video games journalism, in which he claims that it falsely accuses the gaming community of [[Sexism in video gaming|sexism]].<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=https://techraptor.net/content/interview-daniel-vavra|title=An interview with Daniel Vavra: GamerGate and the gaming industry|website=techraptor.net|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-12}}</ref> He has, however, denounced [[misogyny]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Vavra reacts to accusations of racism|url=https://www.gamestar.de/artikel/kingdom-come-deliverance-die-reaktion-auf-die-rassismus-vorwuefe,3324854.html|website=Gamestar.de|accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref> and said that "a large sum of gamers are teenage boys, who [kind of] naturally tend to do stupid things and are often quick on conclusions and insults. So no, the industry is not misogynist. Stupid people are misogynist."<ref name=":1" /> Vavra associated his views on a progressive bias in video game journalism with [[Gamergate controversy|Gamergate]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://kotaku.com/my-e3-meeting-with-a-pro-gamergate-developer-1715511964|title=My E3 Meeting With A Pro-GamerGate Developer|last=Totilo|first=Stephen|work=Kotaku|access-date=2018-02-20|language=en-US}}</ref>
