'''Giorgi Kvirikashvili''' ({{lang-ka|გიორგი კვირიკაშვილი}}; born 20 July 1967) is a [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] politician who was [[Prime Minister of Georgia]] from 30 December 2015 to 13 June 2018. Prior to that he was [[Ministry of Economy and Sustainable Development (Georgia)|Minister of Economy and Sustainable Development]] from 25 October 2012 until 1 September 2015, [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Georgia)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] from 1 September 2015 until 30 December 2015, and Deputy Prime Minister from 26 July 2013 until 30 December 2015. Kvirikashvili has led initiatives to advance Euro-Atlantic and [[European integration]] and highlight Georgia as an attractive location for foreign investment.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.dailyillini.com/article/2015/12/ui-alum-new-georgian-pm|title = University alumnus elected Georgian Prime Minister|website = Daily Illini|access-date = 2016-03-02|deadurl = yes|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160306003242/http://www.dailyillini.com/article/2015/12/ui-alum-new-georgian-pm|archivedate = 2016-03-06|df = }}</ref>  On 20 June 2018, Mamuka Bakhtadze, who previously served as Kvirikashvili's Minister of Finance,<ref>[https://1tv.ge/en/news/pm-nominates-mamuka-bakhtadze-as-the-minister-of-finance/ PM nominates Mamuka Bakhtadze as the Minister of Finance]</ref> was approved by the Georgian Parliament to succeed Kvirikashvili in a 99-6 vote.<ref>https://www.dailysabah.com/europe/2018/06/20/georgia-approves-former-finance-minister-bakhtadze-as-new-premier</ref>

== Education ==
Born in [[Tbilisi]], Kvirikashvili went through the compulsory military service in the [[Soviet army]] from 1986 to 1988. He graduated from the [[Tbilisi State Medical University]] with a degree in Internal Medicine in 1991 and then from the [[Tbilisi State University]] with a degree in Economics in 1995. In 1998, he obtained a [[Master of Science in Finance|master's degree]] in finances from the [[University of Illinois]].<ref name="eco">[http://www.economy.ge/en/george-kvirikashvili George Kvirikashvili] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203015024/http://www.economy.ge/en/george-kvirikashvili |date=2013-12-03 }}. Ministry of Economy and Sustainable Development of Georgia. Retrieved November 30, 2013.</ref>

== Career ==

Kvirikashvili worked as an executive for various banks in Georgia from 1993 to 1999 and as a deputy head of fiscal and monetary office at the State Chancellery of the [[President of Georgia]] in 1999. From 1999 to 2004, he was member of the [[Parliament of Georgia]] on the ticket of [[New Rights]] party.<ref>[http://civil.ge/eng/article.php?id=25355 Ivanishvili's Incoming Cabinet]. [[Civil Georgia]]. October 16, 2012.</ref> After the [[Rose Revolution]] swept [[Mikheil Saakashvili]] to the presidency of Georgia, Kvirikashvili returned to his businesses. From 2006 to 2011, he was Director General of Cartu Bank, owned by the multi-billionaire tycoon [[Bidzina Ivanishvili]]. With Ivanishvili's coming in politics and the victory of his [[Georgian Dream]] coalition over Saakashvili's [[United National Movement (Georgia)|United National Movement]] in the [[Georgian parliamentary election, 2012|October 2012 parliamentary election]], Kvirikashvili was appointed Minister of Economy and Sustainable Development of Georgia in the [[cabinet of Bidzina Ivanishvili]] in October 2012. He additionally assumed the office of Vice Prime Minister in July 2013. He retained both these positions in the succeeding [[Cabinet of Irakli Garibashvili|cabinet]] of [[Irakli Garibashvili]], Ivanishvili's choice as his successor, in November 2013.<ref name="eco"/><ref>[http://civil.ge/eng/article.php?id=26705 New PM Wins Confidence Vote]. [[Civil Georgia]]. November 20, 2013.</ref>

In December 2015, Kviriashvili was nominated by the Georgian Dream coalition as new Prime Minister after Irakli Garibashvili announced his resignation. Kvirikashvili and his incoming [[First Cabinet of Giorgi Kvirikashvili|cabinet]] won the confidence vote in the Parliament with 86 votes to 28 on December 30, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kvirikashvili Confirmed as New Prime Minister|url=http://civil.ge/eng/article.php?id=28892|accessdate=30 December 2015|work=Civil Georgia|date=30 December 2015}}</ref> Kvirikashvili's government is focused on growing the economy and promoting entrepreneurship.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.atlanticcouncil.org/blogs/new-atlanticist/keeping-georgia-s-nato-dream-alive|title = Keeping Georgia’s NATO Dream Alive|last = Sen|first = Ashish|website = Atlantic Council|access-date = 2016-03-02}}</ref> Kvirikashvili has said that he would like to make Georgian–American relations "a backbone of regional stability, economic development, and democratization."<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.atlanticcouncil.org/blogs/new-atlanticist/keeping-georgia-s-nato-dream-alive|title = Keeping Georgia’s NATO Dream Alive|last =|first =|website = Atlantic Council|access-date = 2016-03-02}}</ref>

